<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUL 92 / International Company News: BCE shows 20% downturn
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GIBBENS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MONTREAL
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
BCE, the biggest Canadian telecommunications group, blamed the recession and
lower profits at its Northern Telecom subsidiary for a 20 per cent decline
in second-quarter profits. For the first half, earnings were down 9 per
cent, writes Robert Gibbens in Montreal.
However, despite slow economic recovery, BCE expects improved performance in
all sectors in the second half.
The second-quarter performance was also affected by write-downs at its
Montreal Trustco financial services arm. Final earnings were CDollars 246m
(USDollars 205m), or 72 cents a common share, against CDollars 307m, or 92
cents, a year earlier. Operating revenues were CDollars 4.97bn against
CDollars 5.05bn.
First-half earnings were CDollars 544m, or CDollars 1.60 a common share,
against CDollars 600m, or CDollars 1.80 a share, a year earlier, on revenues
of CDollars 9.84bn against CDollars 9.78bn.
</TEXT>
