<BYLINE>
   By PETER PEARSE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LONDON Merchant Securities, the property and investment group, saw its net
assets per share fall 9 per cent from 109p to 99p over the 12 months to
March 31.
Shareholders' funds declined to Pounds 312m (Pounds 358m) but this fall was
offset partly by the sale in January of 22.5m shares in First Leisure
Corporation, which accrued Pounds 50.7m in profits and represented Pounds
24.7m on the balance sheet.
Also the number of shares in issue fell by 11.5m with the Pounds 131m
acquisition of Westpool Investment Trust, the largest asset of which had
been its 50.9 per cent stake in LMS. Westpool's results were not material,
but the deal simplified the group structure.
Lord Rayne, LMS chairman and from October the successor to Lord Delfont as
chairman of First Leisure, said LMS had retained a 15.2 per cent stake in
the leisure group as 'a measure of confidence' in its management.
First Leisure provided the bulk of the Pounds 7.77m (Pounds 8.68m) share in
the profits of associated undertakings.
Net rental income grew to Pounds 28.9m (Pounds 23.2m), giving operating
profits of Pounds 25m (Pounds 22.1m). Interest payable increased to Pounds
14.8m (Pounds 11.6m) - none has been capitalised - and pre-tax profits fell
to Pounds 24m (Pounds 28.9m).
Mr Robert Spier, finance director, said the group's liquidity, its low
gearing of about 24 per cent, and the fact that virtually all of its Pounds
178m borrowings are at fixed rates - and some 71 per cent beyond the end of
the decade - all displayed the group's soundness.
The final dividend is lifted to a proposed 3p (2.8p) to make 3.8p (3.6p) for
the year.
