<DATE>920724
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUL 92 / Castle in the air bumps down to earth: Euro Disneyland's
opening has been a rocky ride
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALICE RAWSTHORN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Judging by its name, Operation Mickey sounded like a promotion Euro
Disneyland might have mounted to bolster its disappointing attendance
figures. But instead, it was organised by some 500 French farmers who four
weeks ago turned up at the gates of the new theme park outside Paris.
The farmers were protesting against the building of Euro Disney on
agricultural land and against US pressure for reforms to European
agricultural policy. More than 2,000 school children were kept out of the
park until the farmers drove their tractors away after lunch.
Attracting enough French visitors was always going to be one problem facing
Euro Disney. Variable weather - and thus widely fluctuating admissions - was
another.
Although the company is learning how to adapt its product to meet European
tastes and to manage its operations more flexibly, the changes are coming
too slowly to avoid a loss in this fiscal year ending September. It might
not avoid further red ink next year.
Smith New Court, the London broker, forecasts a loss of at least FFr200m
(Pounds 20.4m) for this year, possibly followed by a worse performance next
year, which will include the first winter trading period.
Euro Disney originally hoped for 11m visitors in its first year of
operation. The park has attracted 3.6m people since it opened in April.
Given that spring and summer are expected to have higher than average
attendance levels, this means that, unless there is a sudden improvement,
Euro Disney is unlikely to meet its target.
The crux of the problem is the low number of French visitors who have
accounted for less than 30 per cent of the total, against a forecast of 50
per cent.
Euro Disney does have the consolation that visits from the UK and Germany
are above expectations and foreign visitors tend to spend more as they are
more likely to stay in the resort hotels. However, the six Euro Disney
hotels are performing 'slightly below expectations' with average occupancy
of 70 per cent so far.
There has been an improvement in overall attendance since the start of the
European school holidays. This week Euro Disney has been attracting capacity
crowds with 95 per cent occupancy at the hotels. However, the first year's
attendance is still likely to be 20 per cent lower than expected at less
than 9m people, according to Paribas in London.
This could pose a serious financial problem in that Euro Disney is a highly
geared business with substantial fixed costs, such as interest payments and
amortised construction costs, representing more than 75 per cent of total
costs. That makes it very vulnerable to any reduction in revenue.
The obvious solution is to cut variable costs, chiefly by bringing
employment in line with attendance.
The Disney parks in the US are extremely efficient at this. They have
developed sophisticated forecasting techniques enabling them to alter
staffing levels and food supplies on a daily basis.
Euro Disney plans to make similar adjustments. Mr John Forsgren, finance
director, said staffing levels will vary from 17,000 in the peak summer
season to around 12,500 in the slack winter months. But at present it is
difficult for Euro Disney to forecast accurately.
The California and Florida parks, which opened in 1955 and 1971
respectively, have the benefit of years of data. Euro Disneyland will
eventually build up similar records. Indeed it should be more efficient at
budgeting from next April, when it has its first year of information.
But Euro Disney's forecasting is unlikely ever to be as accurate as its US
counterparts because of its location. First, the climate in Paris is less
predictable than in sunny California and Florida.
Second, the US parks have the advantage of being large tourist attractions
in their areas. This means that Walt Disney World in Florida can use data on
the number of cars crossing the state border to calculate what proportion is
likely to visit the park. By contrast, Euro Disneyland is only one of dozens
of attractions in Paris.
The immediate challenge for Euro Disney is to increase attendance. In some
respects it is not surprising that its performance in the economically
sluggish early 1990s has not met the targets set in the bullish late 1980s.
But Euro Disney also needs to identify which areas should be adapted to suit
European taste.
Catering arrangements have already been changed to increase the availability
of fast food. Euro Disney is in talks with tour operators to change next
year's hotel rates. It is also negotiating winter hotel discounts and
organising an autumn promotional programme for France.
Euro Disney does at least have the consolation that it has performed better
than Tokyo Disneyland, the only other Disney park outside the US. Tokyo
attracted just 2.5m visitors in its first 102 days - against 3.6m for Euro
Disney - and 10.5m visitors in its first year.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 21
</PAGE>
