<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUL 92 / Italy alters privatisation plans: Turnround in policy
threatens credibility of the new Amato government
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ROME
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE ITALIAN government bowed to pressure from foreign bankers, managers of
state groups and politicians yesterday by abandoning a central element of
its radical privatisation plan.
The treasury said it had scrapped its aim, announced just two weeks ago, of
grouping its main industrial and financial sector holdings under two new
umbrella companies in preparation for privatisation.
The plan had aroused fears among foreign bankers over the considerable
foreign debts of Italy's existing state holding companies.
These groups would have been broken up and their assets placed under two new
super-holding companies, raising questions about the fate of the many
foreign loans made to the companies and their subsidiaries.
The Italian treasury had sent shockwaves through the international banking
community in the past week by announcing that the debts of another state
holding company, Efim, would be frozen for up to two years while the group
was broken up.
The plan to reshuffle the state's holdings into just two groups had centred
on IRI, the main state holding group; ENI, the national oil concern; ENEL,
the electricity authority; and INI, the insurance institute. Between them,
these groups owe more than Dollars 10bn (Pounds 5.2bn) to foreign banks.
Professor Guiseppe Guarino, the industry minister who had proposed the
scheme, insisted last night that the radical shake-up of public sector
ownership would now proceed more effectively. But the turnround threatens
the credibility of the new Amato government.
'This is a political setback for the government but probably a step forward
for a more efficient means of reorganising the state sector,' a foreign
banker said.
The four groups, which were recently turned into joint stock companies in
preparation for privatisation, will now remain with the treasury as their
shareholder.
The government gave no formal explanation for abandoning the idea of the two
super-holdings.
Foreign bankers are understood to have expressed concern at the lack of
detail about the structure. They were alarmed at the uncertain legal status
of the foreign debt of the existing groups, particularly IRI, ENI and ENEL.
Bankers were also dissatisfied by the idea that they would be issued with
bonds by the Italian government to back the debts of the two super-holdings,
since it was unclear what interest rate or other terms would apply to the
bonds.
Their fears were heightened by the handling of the freeze on Efim's L8,500bn
(Pounds 3.8bn) debts, of which some L2,300bn is owed to foreign banks.
Only after five days of uncertainty did the treasury clarify that interest
would be paid on Efim's obligations, though not for as much as two years.
The managers of IRI, ENI and ENEL also objected to the plan, since it would
have created a new layer of management which would have effectively put them
out of a job.
Politicians had voiced opposition to the plan because it threatened the
balance of political power of their appointees on the boards.
Under the super-holdings, the government planned to reorganise the companies
in preparation for the privatisation of all or part of their operating
companies. These span virtually every area of industrial and economic
activity.
Italian companies face credit rating scrutiny, Page 26
</TEXT>
