<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUL 92 / MoD's record on contracting criticised
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DANIEL GREEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MINISTRY OF DEFENCE efforts to cut costs by privatising services have been
dogged by errors, delays and mismanagement, according to a government report
published today.
Failure to keep sufficient records meant the amount saved in 13 years of
contracting out was impossible to check, says the National Audit Office, the
government's spending watchdog,
The MoD's problems cast doubt on prospects for plans to extend contracting
out to other departments, the next stage in reforming government machinery.
All government departments have submitted plans to the Cabinet Office to
contract out parts of their work. Sir Peter Levene, the government's
efficiency adviser, is considering the schemes, some of which should be
implemented from this autumn.
MoD failings uncovered by the Audit Office include reporting errors that led
to a 40 per cent overestimate in the amount of cash saved; failing to train
officers how to monitor contractors; and a wrongly assessed catering bid
which led to the work being kept in-house at a cost of Pounds 1m over three
years.
As a result, the audit office recommends that the MoD hives off part of the
contracting-out process itself.
Not all the MoD's efforts were in vain. By 1994, the departmentwill have put
out to competition contracts worth at total Pounds 243m.
However, it says it was 'unable to quantify' MoD claims that contracting out
had cut costs by Pounds 64m a year, an average 24 per cent saving on each
contract. The MoD kept a record only of how much was saved in the first year
of contracting out, even though 'many hundreds of contracts have since been
relet'.
The audit office also notes 'clerical errors' in reporting figures to the
MoD's in-house market testing consultancy .
The MoD said yesterday: 'Market testing in some areas has not progressed as
fast as expected.' It said it had been distracted from the process by more
pressing concerns such as the Gulf war.
It said it had taken steps to improve its guidance and training on
contractor appraisal.
Ministry of Defence: Competition in the Provision of Support Services. HMSO.
Pounds 7.25.
</TEXT>
