<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUL 92 / Barclays move on MCC attacked
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND HUGHES, Law Courts Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AN ATTEMPT by Barclays Bank to stop the administrators of Maxwell
Communication Corporation suing it in the US for the return of Dollars 30m
was an unjustified interference with the US court, the High Court was told
yesterday.
Mr John Higham QC, for the administrators, said Barclays wanted the English
court to help prevent the US court granting remedies in the Chapter 11
bankruptcy proceedings in New York involving MCC for the benefit of the
company's creditors.
He told Mr Justice Hoffmann that the US court should be left to decide
whether it should deal with the dispute.
The firm of administrators, Price Waterhouse, claims that the Dollars 30m
payment in November 1991 - three weeks after the death of Robert Maxwell -
was an unlawful preference. Price Waterhouse contends that it is for it to
choose where to sue for its return to MCC.
The payment had been demanded by Barclays under the terms of an overdraft
facility granted to MCC. The bank remains a creditor of MCC for Pounds
32.3m, about Pounds 7m of which relates to that facility.
Barclays has argued that the English court is the natural forum for trial of
the dispute because the overdraft facility was an English commercial
transaction, governed by English law, to provide working capital for an
English company and its UK subsidiaries.
Mr Higham argued that there were substantial facts supporting the view that
the US court was the natural and appropriate forum.
Barclays had a substantial trading presence in the US and the Dollars 30m
had been paid in New York at Barclays' request.
Judgment will be given on Tuesday.
</TEXT>
