<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUL 92 / Safety net under a steep drop: Exports may be a buffer
between carmakers and the worst of the recession
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GRIFFITHS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A SHARP improvement in the competitiveness of the UK car industry, reflected
in a tripling of exports since the late 1980s, may shield manufacturers from
the worst effects of the decline in the industry.
In spite of record spending on advertising and other promotional carrots to
lure buyers into showrooms, there is a growing sense of unease among
carmakers and dealers that the traditional August surge in sales will be
weaker than previously hoped.
August has assumed enormous importance as it typically accounts for nearly
25 per cent of annual sales because of the introduction on August 1 each
year of the new prefix letter - 'K' this year.
But while August will grab most of the headlines, manufacturers and dealers
have begun looking to September's sales with no less anxiety.
They believe that month's figures, free from the hype surrounding August,
will more accurately reflect whether slight improvements in sales
experienced in April, May and last month - of 9.1 per cent, 1.4 per cent and
4.4 per cent respectively - represent a faint but sustainable recovery.
The growing worry is that the relentless flow of gloomy statistics about the
economy over the past few weeks is damaging the confidence of both private
and business buyers so much that the car market could slip back into
recession for the rest of the year.
Sales have plummeted during the recession by a third from a record 2.3m in
1989 to 1.59m last year. In spite of the recent slight upturn, sales for the
first half of this year were down a further 4 per cent.
Mr Reg Heath, chief executive of the Inchcape-owned TKM group - which
controls more than 100 car dealerships - says there is now a real danger
that any real recovery will not get under way before 1993.
Mr Michael Hollingsworth, an economist with the Society of Motor
Manufacturers and Traders, finds it hard to see how the industry could avoid
cutting production and imposing short-time working this year under those
circumstances.
Without the export programmes, widespread shutdowns would definitely be
unavoidable. But even though some principal continental European markets are
now coming off the boil, and total exports are likely to decline again this
year, the manufacturers at least would no longer face potential disaster.
So far, Ford and Peugeot-Talbot have been the only manufacturers to signal
cuts after workers return from their summer break next month.
And the exports safety-net spread beneath the industry was emphasised again
yesterday with an announcement by Ford of an expanded exports programme at
its Halewood plant on Merseyside, just a few days after announcing that it
would cut output at the plant for a month because of the downturn in UK
sales.
Instead, Escort and Orion models built at Halewood - already exported to
France and Italy - are to go on sale to German buyers as well from the
autumn. As a result, production cuts at Halewood will last for only two
weeks.
The transformation in the UK industry's export performance over the past
three years has been considerable. In 1988 the industry shipped just over
200,000 cars overseas, mainly to continental Europe. By 1990 this had
doubled and last year saw a further sharp rise to 605,000, much higher than
in any year since 1973.
Last year Ford became the UK's biggest motor industry exporter, with
shipments of 186,000 cars and commercial vehicles. Rover Group's exports
totalled 209,000; Peugeot Talbot's 60,000; General Motors' Vauxhall
subsidiary, launching a substantial exports programme for the first time
since the 1970s, shipped 104,000 cars.
As a result, production slipped only 4.53 per cent below the 1990 level, to
1.23m. Output in the first six months of this year, at 686,763, was also
only 1.1 per cent lower than in the same period a year ago.
However, Mr Hollingsworth believes that export markets will weaken further
this year and that total UK exports could drop to around 500,000.
In order even to match 1991's total market, August sales will need to reach
400,000 - against 370,000 last year - and be followed by increases of 4 per
cent on a year-on-year basis for each subsequent month through to December.
The industry is putting a brave public face on its prospects. But privately
fears are being voiced that next month's sales may be no better than the
previous August's, even though the industry is unofficially estimated to be
spending a record Pounds 50m on advertising during July alone to generate
buyer interest. Last year, according to statistical group Market Expenditure
Analysis, it spent Pounds 42m.
In the private-buyer market, worries about job security and the collapse of
the housing market are seen as important factors. This reluctance - rather
than inability - to spend, which is reflected in high personal-savings
ratios, is being intensified, some dealer groups suggest, by a belief among
private buyers that still bigger bargains may be had by delaying purchases.
The attitudes of business car buyers are reflected by the large leasing
groups, which buy a broad spread of cars essentially chosen by their client
companies. They offer manufacturers little comfort.
After the Conservative victory in the general election, new orders started
flowing through the leasing companies at a rate some 40 per cent to 50 per
cent higher than last autumn.
But the spree lasted just eight weeks, as business confidence began
collapsing. 'June 1 was like the tap being turned off,' recalls Mr Ian
Mosley, chief executive of Swan National Leasing and Rental. 'Everything
just stopped.'
</TEXT>
