<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUL 92 / Wales 'set to lead recovery'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTHONY MORETON, Welsh Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE WEAK recovery expected in the second half of this year will be led by
Wales, Mr David Kern, chief economist of National Westminster Bank, said
yesterday.
'The Welsh economy will register a small rise in output of 0.2 per cent this
year compared with fairly large outright declines in London and the rest of
southern England,' he said.
Mr Kern prediced that the resilience of the Welsh economy next year would be
'remarkable'. He pointed out that there had been an increase of just 2 per
cent in unemployment in Wales over the past six months against a national
rise of 7 per cent. 'Over the next year unemployment in Wales is forecast to
rise by 2 per cent compared with 12 per cent in the UK,' he added.
He also forecast that between 1993 and 1997 the Welsh economy would grow on
average by 2.3 per cent a year - more than the 2 per cent forecast for the
UK non-oil economy. He attributed the resilience to 'considerable
restructuring' of the Welsh economy during the 1980s.
'The economy has become much more diversified than 10 years ago,' he said.
There had been 'an increasingly competitive and enterprising manufacturing
sector replacing more traditional industries, while a prominent financial
and business-services sector has become a major source of employment.'
Foreign investment had played a large role in this diversification, Mr Kern
said. 'Wales has succeeded in attracting almost 20 per cent of all inward UK
investment in recent years including substantial amounts of Japanese and
US-owned manufacturing capacity.'
Mr Kern said the outlook for the UK would depend on 'its ability to adjust
successfully to the harsh discipline of convergence to a low-inflation
environment in the European exchange rate mechanism'. He predicted that
Welsh economic performance would comfortably exceed the national average
over the next few years.
</TEXT>
