<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUL 92 / Motorola to spend Pounds 40m on Scots microchip plant
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MOTOROLA, the US electr-onics group, yesterday announced plans to expand its
East Kilbride semiconductor plant in Scotland to make it the biggest of its
kind in Europe. It was the second large investment in Scotland to be
announced by a US electronics group in the past three months.
Motorola proposes to spend Pounds 40m to increase manufacturing capacity at
East Kilbride and to enable the plant to produce a new generation of
microprocessors now manufactured by Motorola only in the US.
National Semiconductor, another large US microchip manufacturer, announced
plans in May to spend Pounds 49.5m expanding its plant at Greenock in
Scotland, creating 250 jobs over two years.
Motorola expects to create 150 jobs at East Kilbride, increasing the plant's
workforce to nearly 2,000 and making the company one of Scotland's biggest
private employers.
Mr Allan Stewart, industry minister for Scotland, welcomed the decision
which he said would enhance the country's position at the forefront of the
European electronics industry.
Scotland accounts for about a fifth of European semiconductor output and
more than half of UK production.
The more than 450 companies involved in the electronics industry in Scotland
employ almost 50,000 people and account for almost a fifth of its
manufacturing output. Just over half of all production is exported to
continental Europe.
Mr Barry Waite, general manager of Motorola's European semiconductor
division, said that it was indicative of the company's commitment to Europe
and East Kilbride that the latest investment was being made when the UK was
fighting to recover from recession. Motorola has already spent Pounds 230m
at East Kilbride since it set up in Scotland in 1969.
The latest investment will allow the plant to manufacture some of the new
68,000 range of microprocessors which are capable of holding far higher
amounts of data on each tiny piece of silicon.
Motorola said: 'We will be able to etch on a piece of silicon measuring 0.5
sq cm a street map of the whole of the UK. Those semi-conductor streets, 0.5
microns wide and 160 times thinner than a human hair, will connect together
more than 6m transistors on the silicon surface.'
Microchips produced at East Kilbride are used in a wide range of products
from cars and CD players to computers and washing machines.
</TEXT>
