<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUL 92 / Warning shots over EC environment rules
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRONWEN MADDOX
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE same environmental standards need to be applied throughout all European
Community countries to avoid creating barriers to trade, Mr Karel van Miert
said last night in London in his first public speech as EC environment
commissioner.
That principle should include drinking water and bathing water, he added.
Mr van Miert's remarks follow a recent statement by Mr Michael Howard, the
UK environment secretary, that some EC environmental directives might be
repealed during the UK's presidency of the EC. This prompted accusations
from opposition MPs and environmental groups that water standards would be
targeted.
Although Mr van Miert will hold the job for only six months until the end of
the current commission, his tenure will coincide with the UK presidency.
His reference to trade barriers reflects concerns that some member states
might impose tough environmental standards not so much to protect the
environment as to keep out imports.
In a speech which also showed that he has adopted some of the policies
favoured by his predecessor, Mr Carlo Ripa di Meana, Mr van Miert said new
taxes should be used alongside regulation to persuade businesses to clean up
the environment.
Taxes on the emission of carbon dioxide and on road haulage were
particularly desirable, he said. One of the UK's priorities in the six
months of its presidency should be to secure EC agreement on how to
stabilise carbon dioxide emissions by the year 2000, he said.
Mr Ripa di Meana was a champion of the carbon tax, a proposal that lost some
of its force with his sudden resignation last month.
The EC's action should not end at its own boundaries, Mr van Miert said.
'The threat posed to our air and our water by the state of nuclear reactors
in central and eastern Europe is the most striking example.'
Mr Howard, who was present for Mr van Miert's speech and later took part in
a debate with him, said enforcement of environmental directives would be a
priority of the UK's presidency.
He also reaffirmed his commitment to subsidiarity - devolving decisions back
to national level. 'We are still looking closely at whether EC environmental
legislation would benefit from shedding weight,' he said.
</TEXT>
