<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUL 92 / High insurance losses feared on mortgages
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
INSURERS may face further heavy losses as a result of continuing high levels
of default on mortgages, analysts believe.
Earlier this year hopes were high that claims from domestic mortgage
indemnity policies, which cover lenders against losses on sales of
repossessed properties, would tail off as the economy moved out of
recession.
However, the continuing depression in the housing market is leading many
analysts to revise earlier forecasts.
Mr Derek Elias, analyst with Paribas Capital Markets Group, said: 'The
problem is not going to to decline fairly rapidly in the tidy way that most
of the lenders and the insurance companies are suggesting.'
Royal Insurance, Sun Alliance, Legal &amp; General and Eagle Star, which
together control about 70 per cent of the mortgage indemnity market, are
worst affected.
Last year insurers made pre-tax losses of Pounds 1.2bn, with mortgage
indemnity claims an important contributing factor.
Overall mortgage indemnity losses for last year and this year were expected
to amount to Pounds 2bn, but could now climb even higher and continue next
year, undermining the prospect of a return to profitability.
Analysts expect repossessions to stay at around the level of 75,540 reached
last year for the next two years.
Mr Youssuf Ziai, analyst with Morgan Stanley, expects repossessions to total
80,000 in 1992. 'People got too excited by the prospects of the government
and building society rescue schemes,' he said.
There are also fears that insurers could face claims on insurance policies
covering securitised mortgage pools.
According to one analyst, the UK industry's exposure on mortgage-pool
business is about Pounds 10bn. Another said he expected claims could amount
to as much as Pounds 100m.
</TEXT>
