<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUL 92 / New shadow cabinet members for John Smith's 'dream team'
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr John Smith, the new Labour leader, yesterday won what amounts to a 'dream
team' in the highly-volatile lottery of the shadow cabinet elections.
The make-up of the new parliamentary leadership reflects a growing shift
towards what is widely becoming known as the 'modernising' faction of the
party with women and southerners getting a slightly larger share of the
cake. A younger generation - comprising Ms Harriet Harman, Ms Marjorie
Mowlam and Mr Chris Smith - can all be deemed Smith loyalists.
The full result of the shadow cabinet election was: Gordon Brown 165 votes,
Tony Blair 150, Robin Cook 149, Frank Dobson 140, John Prescott 137, Bryan
Gould 135, Harriet Harman 135, Marjorie Mowlam 135, Chris Smith 135, Ann
Clwyd 133,Ann Taylor 129, Jack Cunningham 124, Michael Meacher 122, Donald
Dewar 121, David Blunkett 112, Jack Straw 111, Tom Clarke 105, David Clark
104.
Harriet Harman
Robin Cook's well-established deputy on the high-profile shadow health
portfolio and already one of the best-known of Labour's frontbench
spokespeople. Ms Harman is too uncompromising in her campaigning for women's
rights for some of the more unreconstructed male chauvinists in Labour's
ranks but she will be a key figure in the party's bid to woo more of the
female vote. She is approaching her tenth anniversary as MP for the
down-at-heel inner London seat of Peckham and has an enviable reputation as
a diligent constituency worker. A leftwinger of the Meacherite rather than
the Bennite school.
Tom Clarke
Affable MP for Monklands West who has the advantage over his shadow cabinet
colleagues of sharing a constituency border with his party leader. Mr Clarke
is arguably the least well-known of the new leadership outside Westminster
but he built a reputation as an efficient second-ranking spokesman on health
affairs, having served as the backbench foreign affairs committee chairman
from 1983-86. He is centre-right, Roman Catholic, devolutionist and a
Scottish moralist and he will be a doggedly loyal supporter of his friend,
Mr John Smith, when the going gets rough.
David Blunkett
His breakthrough into the shadow cabinet at the fourth attempt should give
him an opportunity to demonstrate that he has more than one string to his
bow. He is MP for Sheffield Brightside and has been a frontbench environment
spokesman. He is Britain's third blind MP, has served on Labour's national
executive committee since 1983 and ran Mr Bryan Gould's ill-starred
leadership campaign. He described the sell-off of the water authorities as
'probably the most disgraceful act of a government intent on turning Britain
into an auctioneer's paradise'.
Chris Smith
Conscientious Islington South and Finsbury MP and previously the Number
Three in the Smith-Beckett shadow Treasury team. He did his prospects no
harm by successfully moving the controversial recent amendment to raise MPs'
office expense allowances by 38 per cent. He is the only MP openly to have
declared his homosexuality. Mr Smith increased his once slender majority by
9,800 votes in the last general election. A softish left intellectual, he
co-sponsored Mr Tony Benn's 1989 bill to disestablish the Church of England.
Marjorie Mowlam
A trojan of Labour's ultimately futile so-called prawn cocktail offensive.
She is an industrious former college lecturer who made a good fist of
shadowing the tricky City and corporate affairs portfolio without ever
giving the impression of having found her metier. She was among the first
members of the parliamentary intake of 1987 to be appointed to the front
bench as a Northern Ireland spokeswoman four years ago. MP for the
industrial north-east constituency of Redcar, she is well-placed now to turn
her attentions to a bigger spending department.
</TEXT>
