<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUL 92 / Banks set to bounce California's cheques: State
administration grapples with severe budget crisis as big pay day looms
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
CALIFORNIAN banks are preparing to bounce the state government's cheques, as
the state grapples with its most severe budget crisis since the Depression.
Left without a formal budget for the fiscal year that began this month, the
state government has been reduced to paying its employees and contractors
with a form of cheque, or IOU, known as a registered warrant. For
recipients, these warrants are meant to be as good as cheques, while the
banks earn interest on them until the state redeems them.
More than Dollars 1bn is already outstanding in this form, a big pay day is
impending next week and banks are starting to grumble. Small community banks
have virtually stopped accepting the IOUs. Bank of America, one of the main
Californian banks, said yesterday it would no longer accept the state's IOUs
from August 5.
'This is a very unusual situation. I don't think anyone has issued scrip or
IOUs since the 1930s,' said Mr Ron Snell at the National Conference of State
Legislatures.
Bankers' threats appear to have forced Governor Pete Wilson of California, a
Republican, and Mr Willie Brown, Speaker of the Democratic-controlled state
assembly, into a new effort to resolve their disagreements. 'It's going to
take this sort of action to get out of the impasse,' said Mr Richard Mount
of the Saratoga National Bank, near San Francisco, noting that the 5 per
cent interest paid to banks on the warrants did not begin to cover handling
costs.
But the size of California's fiscal problems, and the public policy
questions which underlie them, will make it hard to reach a solution.
Faced with a budget shortfall last year, Governor Wilson agreed to a heavy
tax increase. As the state's economy continued to suffer from recession,
however, this failed to bring in as much revenue as hoped.
This year, the state faces a shortfall estimated at Dollars 11bn-Dollars
12bn, for a total budget of Dollars 55bn-Dollars 60bn. 'Even the states
which had very large problems at the beginning of the 1980s, because of the
collapse in oil and energy tax revenues, did not have shortfalls of 20 per
cent,' Mr Snell comments.
The difficulties are rooted in the state's development over the last two
decades and the policies it has pursued. The growing population has put
heavy burdens on public education and social security. The burdens have been
made worse by immigration from elsewhere in the US, Mexico and Pacific Rim
countries.
The state has also taken over from city and county administrations more of
the cost of providing services, as a consequence of the 1978 state
constitutional amendment, known as Proposition 13, that limited property
taxes. Much discussion between Governor Wilson and Speaker Brown focuses on
how to reduce the state's payments to local governments so as to compensate
them for the property tax reduction under Proposition 13.
California has a history of passing by referendum constitutional amendments
which mandate spending or earmark revenues. As a result, its governors
complain they control less than 10 per cent of their budget. The fiscal
crisis has been brought to a head by recession, which has hit California
harder than most other states, and by cuts in defence spending, once a
mainstay in the state economy.
Mr Gray Davis, state controller, said this week that he would start
redeeming some of the IOUs from August 3. The state has about Dollars 1.5bn
in cash, but is constrained in using that until a budget has been passed.
Even so, a longer-term solution is expected to require radical rethinking of
the services California offers its population and the taxes it may levy.
</TEXT>
