<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUL 92 / Suleiman Franjieh, feudal warlord who became president of
Lebanon: Obituary
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
SULEIMAN Franjieh, the former president of Lebanon and one of the country's
last surviving zaim, or feudal clan leaders, has died of heart failure at
the age of 82.
As head of state from 1970 until 1976, Franjieh presided over the beginning
of Lebanon's civil war in April 1975. The following year, he asked his old
friend, President Hafez Al-Assad of Syria, to send 'peace-keeping' troops to
Lebanon. To the dismay of many of Franjieh's fellow Maronite Catholics, some
40,000 Syrian soldiers remain in Lebanon to this day. Their scheduled
withdrawal to eastern Lebanon this autumn is now the country's main focus of
political tension.
In 1957, Suleiman Franjieh led a murder squad into a church in northern
Lebanon to gun down members of the rival Douaihy clan. Franjieh fled to
Damascus where he forged a life-long friendship with Mr Assad, at that time
an air force officer. A longtime foe of an armed Palestinian presence in
Lebanon, Franjieh sent tanks and aircraft to bombard Palestinian camps near
Beirut in 1973. Despite his violent past, Franjieh was respected as a senior
statesman in the Middle East. Unlike many other Maronite leaders, he always
stressed the importance of Lebanon's Arab identity and good relations with
Syria.
He held court at two homes in the northern Lebanese cities of Zghorta and
Ehden, smoking cigarettes through a black holder and recalling the details
of his long life with surprising lucidity. When he entered hospital in
Beirut recently with heart trouble, his bodyguards occupied a whole floor of
the American University Hospital while the Lebanese president, prime
minister, speaker of the assembly and a host of parliamentarians called to
pay their respects. The life of the 'Lion of Ehden' was repeatedly marred by
violence.
He had groomed his son, Tony, for leadership of the powerful northern
Lebanese family.
Tony Franjieh had established the Marada (Giants) militia. But in 1978, the
leader of the rival Maronite Phalangist militia, Bashir Gemayel, dispatched
gunmen to the family's home in Ehden to massacre Tony Franjieh, his wife,
infant daughter and 30 family retainers.
Suleiman Franjieh harboured untold bitterness towards the Gemayels and the
Phalange.
But in recent years he channelled his hopes and energies into preparing his
grandson Suleiman - Tony's son - to continue the family's political role in
Lebanon.
Young Suleiman served as a minister without portfolio in the last two
Lebanese governments, but resigned in anger last month when Samir Geagea,
the Phalange leader who is believed to have carried out the 1978 Ehden
massacre, arrived at a luncheon given by the Lebanese president Elias Hrawi.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 3
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT923-11465</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CGXAXADVFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920724
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUL 92 / Community spending cut in draft budget
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW HILL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
EUROPEAN Community budget ministers yesterday agreed to scale back
Commission spending proposals for 1993, overruling the wishes of poorer
member states.
Ministers agreed that total EC spending should be cut from Ecu63.1bn
(Dollars 85.18bn) this year to Ecu62.9bn in 1993. However, the draft budget
now goes to the European parliament which has the power to make substantial
amendments.
Negotiations over next year's budget are separate from the fierce debate
over the 1993-97 budget proposals going on among foreign and finance
ministers. But wealthier countries are still likely to use yesterday's deal
to back their claim that the EC has money to spare. They say there is no
need to increase the contributions of member states on the scale suggested
by Brussels in its five-year plan.
Proposed expenditure for 1993 would be equivalent to a contribution from
member states of just 1.09 per cent of gross national product - well below
the current revenue ceiling of 1.2 per cent.
The Commission has said the ceiling must be increased to 1.37 per cent by
1997, but richer countries argue there is plenty of 'headroom' under the
current ceiling.
One element in the draft budget likely to be attacked in the European
parliament is the decision to omit a specific figure for the 'cohesion fund'
to help poorer EC economies catch up.
The ministers included a specific line for a cohesion fund in the 1993
draft, but rejected the Commission's suggested figure of Ecu1.56bn, despite
the protests of Greece, Portugal, Ireland and Spain, which would benefit
most.
The maximum committed spending under the draft agreed yesterday would drop
from Ecu66.6bn this year to Ecu65.7bn in 1993. That compares with the
Commission's proposal that commitments should rise to Ecu69.3bn.
The proposed budget gives effect to the reform of the common agricultural
policy, but will involve cuts in other areas. For example, the European
consumers' organisation has already complained that funding designed for
consumer protection had been halved.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 2
</PAGE>
