   MONTREAL
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
BCE, the biggest Canadian telecommunications group, said the recession and
lower profits at its Northern Telecom subsidiary caused a 20 per cent
decline in second-quarter profits. For the first half, earnings were down 9
per cent.
However, despite slow economic recovery, BCE expects improved performance in
all sectors in the second half.
The second-quarter performance was also affected by write-downs at its
Montreal Trustco financial services arm. Final earnings were CDollars 246m
(USDollars 205m) or 72 cents a common share, against CDollars 307m, or 92
cents, a year earlier. Operating revenues were CDollars 4.97bn against
CDollars 5.05bn.
First-half earnings were CDollars 544m, or CDollars 1.60 a common share,
against CDollars 600m, or CDollars 1.80 a share, a year earlier, on revenues
of CDollars 9.84bn against CDollars 9.78bn.
BCE said first-half telecommunications earnings were flat because of the
recession.
Bell Canada, the telecommunications utility providing most of BCE's
earnings, saw slower growth. Its first-half profit gained a modest 1.2 per
cent and operating revenues rose 2.4 per cent.
Bell Canada contributed CDollars 453m, or CDollars 1.47 a share, to BCE's
first-half earnings, unchanged from a year earlier. Northern Telecom
contributed 34 cents per BCE share against 38 cents.
