<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUL 92 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICIA MORISON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Kirghiz came to the Prophet Mohammed late in history, and it seems they
did not take tremendously to his message. From Marx to the Market (C4, 7.20)
is the last in the splendid series on Central Asia, The Crescent and the
Star.
What can a scriptwriter do these days to make a detective different?
Aristocratic, black, oriental, disabled, female. . . we've seen them all.
Virtual Murder which starts tonight (BBC1, 9.30) comes up with an academic
with time on his hands - a rare bird these days. But then, he is a criminal
psychologist, which should give him a head start.
Glyndebourne Gala (BBC2, 8.30) presents a star-studded list of artists,
including Frederica von Stade, Ruggiero Raimondi and Felicity Lott, singing
a rag-bag of arias to mark the last night in the old opera-house. And
opportunity for Glyndebourne habitues to shed a sentimental tear, and for
the rest of us to wonder what all the fuss is about.
If you own a place across the Channel and want to upgrade from Bizzy
Lizzies, try Le Manoir (C4, 9.30), which relates how 8 acres in Brittany
were transformed into an English garden.
</TEXT>
