<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUL 92 / Improvement seen in property market
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTHONY MORETON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Welsh property market ended 1991-92 on a positive note even though the
year and its predecessor had been two of the worst in the market since the
late 1950s, Mr Geoffrey Inkin, chairman of the Land Authority for Wales,
said yesterday.
He said when presenting the authority's annual report in Cardiff that the
organisation had made a profit of Pounds 3.3m before tax last year on
turnover of Pounds 9.1m.
That showed a rise in profit of Pounds 400,000 over the previous year on a
turnover which was Pounds 500,000 lower.
However, encouraging signs included the announcement of a new community
development with some 2,000 houses and light industrial and retail areas on
a 370-acre site in Cardiff, and the involvement of the property arm of
Boots, the retail chain, in the redevelopment of the town centre in
Caerphilly.
The authority was set up in 1974 to help development in Wales by putting
together packages of land. It is particularly active where the private
sector has difficulty acquiring land and is the only body of its kind in
Britain.
It took 14 years to assemble the land for the Cardiff development.
Mr Inkin said the authority would 'maintain an even more imaginative
programme this year' in order to prepare the foundations for recovery once
the national economy picked up.
Mr Bernard Ryan, chief executive, said that as a result of its land sales
last year 'a potential development investment in Wales of Pounds 70m would
come about'.
Land Authority for Wales Annual Report. LAW, Customhouse St, Cardiff CF1
5AP. Free.
</TEXT>
