Union Pacific, the US transportation company, yesterday reported a 35 per
cent rise in second-quarter profits, at Dollars 206m after tax, writes Nikki
Tait. The advance lifted net profits for the first months to Dollars 351m,
compared with Dollars 286m in the same period of 1991.
At the operating level, second-quarter figures improved more modestly -
profits were up 15 per cent at Dollars 376m - but the company said there had
been 'strong gains' in all its businesses.
The railroad division pushed up earnings by almost 9 per cent at Dollars
158m and, despite a two-day shutdown in June, car loadings rose by 2 per
cent.
*****
Hershey Foods, the largest publicly-traded manufacturer of chocolate and
confectionery products in the US, saw second-quarter profits rise to Dollars
34.5m after tax, from Dollars 31.9m a year earlier, writes Nikki Tait.
This takes after-tax earnings for the first six months of the year to
Dollars 93.4m, compared with Dollars 80.5m.
*****
Wall Street brokerage house, Bear Stearns, yesterday agreed to work with a
recently-formed consortium of seven Spanish banks to promote asset
securitisation in Spain, writes Patrick Harverson.
This is its second foray into Europe under the asset securitisation banner.
In 1989 it set up a similar joint venture in France with Credit Lyonnais.
*****
Dr Pepper/Seven-Up, the third largest soft-drinks group in the US, announced
a 13 per cent increase in second-quarter operating profits, to Dollars
46.5m, writes Patrick Harverson.
After interest expense of Dollars 39.6m, a Dollars 6m charge to cover the
costs of cancelling a Dollars 600m public stock offering, and Dollars 4.6m
in minority interest dividend, however, the group recorded a net loss of
Dollars 2.2m in the quarter. Last time Dr Pepper made a net profit of
Dollars 2.2m.
