</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GIBBENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IMPERIAL Oil, Canada's biggest integrated oil company and 70 per cent-owned
by Exxon, says its performance is firmly on the mend after the 1991 roller
coaster caused by the Gulf war.
Second-quarter earnings were CDollars 58m (USDollars 48.3m), or 30 cents a
share, up from CDollars 5m, or 3 cents, in the corresponding period of 1991.
Revenues totalled CDollars 2.33bn against CDollars 2.35bn a year earlier.
In the first half, earnings were CDollars 108m, or 51 cents, against
CDollars 201m, or Dollars 1.04, a year earlier. Much of the 1991 period's
profit was due to the effect of the Gulf war. First-half revenues were
CDollars 4.4bn against CDollars 4.76bn.
Imperial said cash provided from operations in the first half, after
dividends, was CDollars 375m against CDollars 290m. Operating expense was
down 15 per cent to CDollars 246m.
'We have set a direction that will restore earnings to acceptable levels,'
said Mr Arden Haynes, chairman.
In resource operations better heavy oil prices and higher synthetic oil
production more than offset declines in conventional oil output. Petroleum
products margins contracted, while chemicals were strong in the second
quarter.
</TEXT>
