<HEADLINE>
FT  23 JUL 92 / Civil servant's exit sparks sharp reaction
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN, Public Policy Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THERE WAS sharp reaction yesterday to the news that Sir Peter Kemp, the top
civil servant spearheading the government's Civil Service reforms, had been
forced into early retirement.
Sir Peter, permanent secretary at the Office of Public Service and Science,
is to retire in September, two years before the normal Civil Service
retirement age of 60. He is leaving after being told that there was no
longer a job for him to do.
The Association of First Division Civil Servants (FDA) said yesterday that
many members would be 'astounded' at the news. His work in establishing 75
executive agencies in which more than half the Civil Service now worked had
been 'an unprecedented achievement'.
Mr Giles Radice, the senior Labour member of the Commons Treasury and Civil
Service committee, said Sir Peter's departure was the result of 'outrageous
manoeuvring'.
'This is clearly a case of Peter Kemp's face not fitting,' he said. 'To boot
out this highly capable and energetic civil servant in this manner is very
shabby treatment.'
Mr William Waldegrave, the public service minister who is responsible for
the Civil Service, is understood to want a new head for his department,
which was created after the general election.
The department is in charge of the Citizen's Charter, along with the
programme of contracting out Civil Service work and the creation of
executive agencies to deliver government services.
Mr Radice said that the announcement of Sir Peter's departure had been
delayed until the parliamentary recess to avoid questioning by MPs. He
intended to question Mr Waldegrave about the matter when the minister
appeared before the select committee in the autumn.
Sir Peter's successor as head of the OPSS is to be Mr Richard Mottram, the
deputy secretary at the Ministry of Defence. Mr Mottram, who is 47, has been
in charge of the 'options for change' programme to cut the UK armed forces.
He was private secretary to both Sir John Nott and Mr Michael Heseltine when
they were at the Defence Ministry.
Also announced yesterday was the appointment of Sir Geoffrey Holland as
permanent secretary at the Education Department when Sir John Caines retires
in January 1993. Sir Geoffrey, at present permanent secretary at the
Employment Department, was director of the Manpower Services Commission
between 1981 and 1988.
The new head of the Employment Department will be Mr Nick Monck, second
permanent secretary at the Treasury. Mr Andrew Turnbull, principal private
secretary to Mrs Thatcher and Mr Major, will succeed Mr Monck.
Observer, Page 17
</TEXT>
