<HEADLINE>
FT  23 JUL 92 / Consumer demand remains weak
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WEAK consumer demand has been underlined by government figures published
yesterday showing that retail sales volumes fell 0.2 per cent last month
compared with May.
The seasonally adjusted figures show that people are still refraining from
large increases in shop spending, a factor holding back recovery.
On an underlying basis, retail sales have shown a small increase since
earlier this year after a flat period between the third quarter of 1991 and
the first quarter of this year.
With shop sales accounting for about a quarter of the economy, though, Mr
Norman Lamont, the chancellor, needs a much bigger increase if anything
other than a fragile upturn is to develop in coming months.
Retail sales volumes in the second quarter were 0.6 per cent up on the first
quarter. They showed a 1.3 per cent rise on the corres-ponding period last
year.
On a quarter-on-quarter basis, food retailing showed a 0.7 per cent rise in
the April - June period, while non-food businesses increased sales volumes
by 0.2 per cent. Shops selling clothing and footwear showed a 2 per cent
increase in the second quarter compared with the first, and retailers in
household goods saw a 1 per cent fall.
The small decrease in sales volumes for the retail sector last month
compared with May contrasted with market expectations of a 1 per cent
increase. It came after a revised 0.4 per cent rise in sales volumes between
April and May.
The British Retail Consortium, a trade body for the sector, said June had
been 'difficult' for most retailers. One bright spot had been good sales of
fruit and vegetables, and food and drink generally. Sales of furniture and
carpets had been depressed because of the flat housing market.
</TEXT>
