<HEADLINE>
FT  23 JUL 92 / Construction industry recession is worsening
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR, Construction Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE deepest recession to afflict the construction industry for more than
half a century is getting worse, according to government figures published
yesterday.
These indicated that construction orders during the three months to the end
of May fell by 16 per cent compared with the previous three months and by 9
per cent compared with the March - May period last year.
A separate survey of 140 English and Welsh estate agents, also published
yesterday, confirmed the lack of recovery in either house prices or sales.
The Royal Institution of Chartered Surveyors, which conducted the study,
appealed to the government to double the threshold at which stamp duty
becomes payable on house purchases from Pounds 30,000 to Pounds 60,000.
A government concession to withdraw stamp duty for purchases of up to Pounds
250,000 ends next month. The ending of the concession has been strongly
criticised by housebuilders and estate agents.
The institution said that raising the threshold to Pounds 60,000 would
assist first-time buyers.
Slightly more than 41 per cent of agents questioned by the institution said
that house prices had continued to fall during the three months to the end
of June. A further 57 per cent said prices had remained static. Less than 1
per cent reported a price increase.
Mr Peter Miller, an official at the institution, said there was no
improvement in the market, even if the worst of the price falls appeared to
be over.
Figures from the Department of the Environment showed that the value of
construction orders for private homes, in constant 1985 prices, fell by 11
per cent during the three months to the end of May compared with the
previous three months, and was 13 per cent lower than during the
corresponding period last year.
Private industrial orders for the three months to May were 24 per cent lower
than in the previous three months, and 21 per cent lower than during the
March - May period last year.
Private commercial orders, mainly for offices and shops, were 9 per cent
lower than both the previous three months and the corresponding period a
year before.
Public-works orders - which cover roads, hospitals and other infrastructure
 -were 14 per cent and 5 per cent lower respectively.
Only public-housing and housing association orders for the three months to
May showed any improvement. They were 34 per cent lower than in the previous
three months but 89 per cent higher than in the corresponding period last
year.
</TEXT>
