<HEADLINE>
FT  23 JUL 92 / Coal's sell-off faces pitfalls: Profits disguise questions
over contracts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JULIET SYCHRAVA
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ONE British Coal board member said ruefully at lunch: 'Any other company
would have been sticking its chest out.'
The company yesterday announced a Pounds 170m profit for the year to March,
its best yet and a promising prelude to its forthcoming privatisation.
But questions, not congratulations, hung in the air at British Coal's
headquarters.
That Pounds 170m is testimony to the fact that British Coal is now more
efficient than ever before. But it was almost all earned from British Coal's
contract with the electricity industry, put in place by the government and
expiring in March.
Moreover, until new contracts are settled in the coming months British
Coal's future revenue and profit are uncertain.
The message from British Coal yesterday was that this is the last year of
big profits. Next year, according to Mr Neil Clarke, the chairman, the
company will not match this year's big increase. The reason is that the
contract with the generators will still be in place.
He said yesterday that there might, however, be a 'cliff edge' in the second
half of the year if the new contracts with the generators meant that the
company had to start closing collieries quickly and writing them off against
profits.
The company's future would then hinge on the new contracts. British Coal has
made an offer to the generators, understood to be based on a price of Pounds
1.50 a unit of energy from coal. It is understood to include a volume of 40m
tonnes at the start of the contract, falling perhaps to around 25m over a
five-year period.
That compares with Pounds 1.85 a unit today and a volume of 65m tonnes.
Revenues and profits, as Mr Clarke admitted, will inevitably fall.
British Coal can try to squeeze out more costs and boost productivity. This
year's profits show big productivity gains, admittedly from a low base.
Output per manshift rose 13 per cent over the past year, and so far this
year it has risen a further 14.6 per cent. Mr Clarke said there would be
additional improvements.
Costs - of which the wage bill is the most substantial - fell only a couple
of per cent, and there seems little sign that they can be tightened further.
The background is that the UK market for coal is shrinking and British
Coal's task is being complicated by competing fuels, notably gas.
'The total market for black fuels (coal, heavy fuel oil, and similar
products) will be 60m tonnes,' Mr Ken Moses, British Coal's joint deputy
chairman said. 'The issue, then, is how will the generators react to that?
It is con-ceivable that they could not take a coal contract at all.'
In the worst scenario, he said, British Coal might end up supplying only 20m
tonnes to the UK electricity market, compared with 65m today.
That makes it hard to see why anyone should be interested in buying British
Coal when it is privatised some time after the contracts have been signed.
Some potential buyers admit they find it hard to value the company.
'I always find British Coal's results very academic,' said the head of one
international company's coal division. Its prices and tonnages were
artificial, he added.
The company had a level of profitability 'you wouldn't expect in the
industry', he said. The reason for this was that coal had 'an exceptionally
high price that was forced on the customer'.
Even so, Mr David McErlain, chairman of Anglo-United, the fuel group,
believes the profit has a positive message for potential buyers.
'It's an exceptional performance in the year when they needed it, that is
just before privatisation,' he says. 'They deserve enormous credit for that,
and they deserve credit for pushing through the colliery closures that
helped them achieve it.'
While acknowledging that nobody can say what volumes British Coal can sell
at what price after March 1993, Mr McErlain believes the profits show that
costs can be squeezed out of the business.
'A purchaser will look at the strength of the contract with the generators,
and then he'll take his own view on what costs can come out. After that,
it's a financial exercise.'
Until more details emerge of how the mines will be packaged, most potential
bidders are keeping quiet.
Peabody, the US coal company which is part of the Hanson group, is thought
to be a prime candidate.
Hanson was reticent about British Coal's results. 'It is not for us to
comment,' Hanson said. 'But we've said that, if the government decided to
sell it through a trade sale, we'd have a look at it.' RTZ, the
international mining group, said it had no comment.
British Coal's Mr Clarke, himself a former chairman of an international
mining group, says the company would provide a buyer with a strategic
foothold in the UK market, the only relatively open market in Europe and one
that may open up further.
British Coal's future profit is uncertain. What is certain, however, is that
whoever buys the company is unlikely to get it to outperform yesterday's
record result.
</TEXT>
