<HEADLINE>
FT  23 JUL 92 / S African strike looms as talks fail
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP GAWITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SOUTH AFRICA faces the renewed prospect of industrial strife, after the
breakdown yesterday of talks between business and labour aimed at averting a
lengthy general strike next month.
'An historic opportunity has been thrown away by employers,' the 1.3m-strong
Congress of South African Trade Unions (Cosatu) said. It had no option but
to go ahead with plans for a stoppage 'for the week of August 3'.
Cosatu, the largest union grouping in the country, had been holding talks
for the past two weeks with the South African Co-ordinating Committee on
Labour Affairs (Saccola), an umbrella employer body.
The two parties had hoped to negotiate a pact that would avoid a general
strike and help break the country's constitutional deadlock.
They agreed a draft charter for 'peace, democracy and economic
reconstruction', but then apparently both sides had difficulties in
persuading their constituencies to go along with them.
Cosatu said the parties failed to ratify the draft accord because of
differences about a compromise one-day shutdown on August 3, which was
proposed instead of a longer all-out strike.
The one-day shutdown would have been a voluntary exercise, in which both
business and labour would have participated.
Their fruitless efforts coincided with an escalation in the mass action
campaign of the African National Congress (ANC) and its allies.
This week has seen the ANC embark on an extended series of sit-ins in
government offices, police stations and magistrates' courts.
Protests yesterday included shoppers running up bills at tills of leading
stores and then refusing to pay.
Demonstrators also gathered at the Pretoria central prison, demanding an end
to township violence and a swift transition to democracy.
More than 1,000 protesters have been arrested since Monday, although few
have been held for long in police custody.
The United Nations special envoy to South Africa, Mr Cyrus Vance, yesterday
met President F W de Klerk.
Mr Vance's trip, which springs from a UN Security Council resolution last
week, is aimed at creating a climate for negotiations.
The envoy held two hours of talks with Mr de Klerk, who briefed him on the
government's position on constitutional talks with the ANC and other
black-led parties and on the country's wave of violence.
Mr Vance is scheduled to meet the ANC and the Zulu-based Inkatha Freedom
party today.
The ANC withdrew from talks on a multi-racial constitution last month in
protest at the massacre of at least 43 people at Boipatong township. It
accused Mr de Klerk of condoning the attack and of trying to cling to
minority rule.
Toyota and the National Union of Metalworkers have signed an agreement
ending the two-month strike at the Japanese company's Durban manufacturing
plants, opening the way for the re-employment of 6,000 sacked workers.
</TEXT>
