<HEADLINE>
FT  23 JUL 92 / Poor trade and sales figures add to UK economic gloom
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
POOR TRADE and retail sales figures yesterday added to growing evidence that
the UK economy is failing to recover from recession.
The figures, revealing a fall in high street sales and a sharp drop in
exports last month, increased nervousness on the London stock market, where
the FT-SE 100 share index ended 27.7 lower at 2,387.9.
They also depressed the pound, which closed in London at DM2.8325, just a
quarter of a pfennig above its lowest close since joining the European
exchange rate mechanism in October 1990. In late trading in New York it was
at DM2.8328.
The Central Statistical Office data, showing a 0.2 per cent drop in retail
sales in June and a 2.5 per cent monthly drop in the value of imports,
indicated that consumer demand is still muted.
The fall in imports was outstripped by a drop in exports, reflecting
weakening overseas markets. The value of exports fell by 3.5 per cent from
Pounds 9.2bn in May to Pounds 8.8bn in June.
This caused the visible trade deficit to deteriorate from Pounds 830m in May
to a seasonally adjusted Pounds 922m in June. The current account deficit,
which includes a projected Pounds 200m surplus from 'invisible' trade, such
as services and transfers, was estimated by the CSO to have increased last
month to Pounds 722m from Pounds 630m in May.
The underlying deficit, which excludes oil and erratic items, such as
aircraft and precious stones, remained stable at Pounds 1.2bn, the same as
in May.
